thnicity and empire, and gendered imagery. The important contribution of this study lies especially in its identification of patterns of ideological continuity and variation within the reigns of individual rulers, between various localities, and between the different rulers of this period, and in its discussion of the place of Early Neo-Assyrian state ideology in the overall development of Assyrian propaganda. It includes several indexed appendices, which list all primary sources, present all divine and royal epithets, and provide all of the “royal visual representations,” and incorporates numerous illustrations, such as maps, plans, and royal iconography.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aGodsxPolitical aspectszAssyriaxHistoryvSources. 0aIdeologyxPolitical aspectszAssyriaxHistoryvSources. 0aImperialismxHistoryyTo 1500vSources. 0aPower (Social sciences)zAssyriaxHistoryvSources. 4aAshurnasirpal II. 4aNeo-Assyrian. 4aShalmaneser III. 4apropaganda. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070100508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2016z9783110485097oZDB-23-DGD0 cEPUBz97816145196830 cprintz978161451744340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978161451691040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781614516910423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781614516910.jpg  a978-3-11-070100-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aP